## Cursor-Specific Workflow

### Context — Always Provide Before Coding
- Use `@file` to attach directly relevant files before asking Cursor to write or edit code
- Use `@codebase` for broad questions about how the project works
- Use `@docs` when working with a library that has indexed documentation
- Attach `AI_CONTEXT.md` at the start of a new session to orient Cursor on the project

### Composer vs Chat
| Use Composer when... | Use Chat when... |
|----------------------|-----------------|
| Writing or editing code across one or more files | Asking questions or exploring an idea |
| Executing a scoped task end-to-end | Getting an explanation of existing code |
| Running a multi-step implementation | Comparing approaches before committing |

### Scoping Agent Runs
- Give Composer one clearly defined task at a time
- Include a constraints block in every Composer prompt (see `22-constraints.md`)
- After Composer finishes, review the diff before accepting — treat output as a draft
- If Composer goes off-track, cancel and restart with a tighter, more explicit prompt

### Useful Prompt Patterns in Cursor
- `@file:path/to/file.ts` — scope the task to a specific file
- `@selection` — act only on the highlighted code
- "Do not modify any other files" — explicit scope constraint
- "Show me a plan before writing any code" — get approval before execution